{% extends "_base.njk" %}
{% set description = "How the Freedom and Dignity Project builds change, organized people, real defined demands, and a coalition that holds institutions accountable." %}
{% block title %}Our Approach — Freedom and Dignity Project{% endblock %}
{% block og_description %}Good policy doesn't become law by accident. It takes organized people, real defined demands, and a coalition willing to hold institutions accountable. Here's how we're building that.{% endblock %}
{% block og_url %}approach.html{% endblock %}
{% block twitter_description %}Good policy doesn't become law by accident. It takes organized people, real defined demands, and a coalition willing to hold institutions accountable.{% endblock %}
{% block content %}
<header class="page-hero-standard">
  <span class="hero-eyebrow">How We're Building This</span>
  <h1>Our <span>Approach</span></h1>
  <p class="hero-statement">Good policy doesn't become law by accident. It takes organized people, real defined demands, and a coalition willing to hold institutions accountable.</p>
</header>

<!-- THE PROBLEM WITH PLATFORMS -->
<section class="bg-cream ruled" aria-labelledby="platforms-heading">
<div class="wrap">
  <div class="eyebrow" style="color:var(--mid)">Why Most Platforms Fail</div>
  <h2 id="platforms-heading">A Policy Document Isn't a Movement</h2>
  <p>Think tanks publish excellent policy. It sits on shelves. Progressive coalitions draft detailed platforms. They get ignored after election day. The gap between good ideas and enacted law isn't a knowledge problem, it's a power problem.</p>
  <p>Ideas without organized people behind them are just ideas. The question is never "do we have good enough policy?" The question is always "who is going to make this happen, and how?" That is the work this project is built around.</p>
</div>
</section>

<!-- THEORY OF CHANGE -->
<section class="bg-dark on-dark ruled" aria-labelledby="theory-heading">
<div class="wrap">
  <div class="eyebrow">The Theory of Change</div>
  <h2 id="theory-heading">Defined Demands. Accountable Institutions.</h2>
  <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,.75);max-width:640px;margin-bottom:2rem">Every successful movement in American history, labor, civil rights, suffrage, organized around concrete, specific demands. Not vibes. Not platforms. Demands. Things that could be passed, signed, implemented, and checked. When the demand is concrete, accountability is possible. When accountability is possible, power shifts.</p>

  <div class="policyos-layers">
    <div class="layer-card">
      <div class="layer-card-num">Step 1</div>
      <div class="layer-card-title">Define the Demands</div>
      <div class="layer-card-body">Every position in this project has a canonical ID, a legal basis, a formal policy statement, and a plain-language summary. Not principles, demands. Numbered. Traceable. Specific enough that a legislator either votes for them or doesn't. <a href="policy-library.html" style="color:var(--gold)">See the full policy library →</a></div>
    </div>
    <div class="layer-card">
      <div class="layer-card-num">Step 2</div>
      <div class="layer-card-title">Build the Coalition</div>
      <div class="layer-card-body">The positions are modular by design. A progressive and a libertarian can both find things here they believe in. A Republican who cares about corruption can adopt the anti-corruption policy area. The goal isn't ideological purity, it's a broad coalition organized around shared structural demands.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="layer-card">
      <div class="layer-card-num">Step 3</div>
      <div class="layer-card-title">Hold the Line</div>
      <div class="layer-card-body">When any candidate, party, or institution claims to stand for freedom, dignity, and accountability, they answer to a specific ledger. Not vague values, numbered positions. The demands don't change based on who's running. That consistency is how accountability works.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- NOT AFFILIATED -->
<section class="bg-parchment ruled" aria-labelledby="independent-heading">
<div class="wrap">
  <div class="eyebrow" style="color:var(--mid)">Who This Is For</div>
  <h2 id="independent-heading">Not a Party. A Set of Demands.</h2>

  <div class="arch-intro" style="gap:1.75rem">
    <div class="arch-item">
      <div class="arch-item-label">No Affiliation</div>
      <p>This project is not affiliated with any candidate, party, or campaign. Its positions belong to anyone who wants to use them. A candidate can run on them. A party can adopt them. An organizer can use them to pressure incumbents. The point isn't to build a new party, it's to shift the terrain so that every party has to answer to a higher bar.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="arch-item">
      <div class="arch-item-label">Evidence, Not Ideology</div>
      <p>Every factual claim is held to the standard of a published policy document. Primary sources first. Adversarial review required, every claim must survive an active attempt to disprove it. Counterevidence is acknowledged, not buried. When the evidence is genuinely unclear, this project says so. Conviction is necessary for political action. Evidence is what distinguishes conviction from ideology.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="pullquote">
    The goal is to establish a set of structural demands that become the baseline expectation of any institution that wants to be taken seriously on freedom, accountability, and the material conditions of a dignified life.
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- HOW THE POLICY IS BUILT -->
<section class="bg-cream ruled" aria-labelledby="built-heading">
<div class="wrap">
  <div class="eyebrow" style="color:var(--mid)">Under the Hood</div>
  <h2 id="built-heading">The Policy Framework</h2>
  <p>The policy positions are built on a deliberate architecture, values that cannot be traded away, cross-cutting design principles, and specific enforceable positions. Every policy area has a foundation. Every position has a canonical ID. Nothing here is accidental.</p>
  <p><a href="platform.html">See the full platform architecture →</a></p>
</div>
</section>

<div class="page-nav-cta">
  <div class="wrap">
    <p>Ready to get involved? Here's how to contribute.</p>
    <a href="get-involved.html" class="btn-primary">Get Involved →</a>
  </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}
